It injects four new columns into your data: source, year, month, and day. These are based on the arguments passed by the Step Function and the current UTC time.

3. Writing to S3 and the Glue Data Catalog
This is the crucial part:

Python


df_partitioned.write \
    .mode("append") \
    .format("parquet") \
    .partitionBy("source", "year", "month", "day") \
    .option("path", args['PROCESSED_S3_PATH']) \
    .saveAsTable(f"{args['DATABASE_NAME']}.{args['TARGET_TABLE']}")
Format: It converts the data from CSV into Snappy Parquet (a highly compressed, columnar format).

Storage: It saves these Parquet files into a new S3 bucket path (PROCESSED_S3_PATH), organizing them into folders by source and date (e.g., source=lims/year=2026/month=07/day=03/).

Registration: .saveAsTable registers this S3 location as a table in the AWS Glue Data Catalog (under the provided database and table names).